            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is Loan-to-Value (LTV)?</h2>
              <p>
                Loan-to-Value (LTV) is a percentage that compares the amount of
                a loan to the value of the asset used as collateral, typically a
                property. It is one of the key indicators lenders use to measure
                risk when they assess a mortgage or secured loan.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">LTV formula</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{LTV (\%)} = \frac{\text{Loan amount}}{\text{Property
                  value}} \times 100 \]
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-0">
                  Example: a loan of 180,000 on a property worth 240,000 gives
                  \[ \text{LTV} = \frac{180{,}000}{240{,}000} \times 100 = 75\%.
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use the LTV calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the property value</strong> – usually the lower
                  of purchase price and appraised value.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose how to describe your financing</strong>:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Enter the <strong>loan amount</strong> directly, or</li>
                    <li>
                      Enter your <strong>down payment</strong> (amount or %) and
                      let the tool compute the loan.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally, enter a <strong>maximum allowed LTV</strong> (for
                  example 80%) to see the maximum safe loan and any extra equity
                  needed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Read the <strong>LTV result</strong>, risk band, and key
                  figures on the right.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Interpreting your LTV result</h2>
              <p>
                Lenders typically group LTV into ranges, each with different
                conditions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>≤ 60% – very low LTV</strong><br />
                  Strong equity position, best risk profile. Often eligible for
                  the most competitive interest rates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>60–80% – standard LTV</strong><br />
                  Typical for many mortgages. Rates are still generally good,
                  but slightly higher than very low LTV.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>80–90% – higher LTV</strong><br />
                  Higher risk for the lender. You may face stricter
                  underwriting, higher rates, or insurance requirements.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>&gt; 90% – very high LTV</strong><br />
                  Maximum-risk band. Only some lenders or special products allow
                  this, often with higher costs and tighter conditions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Why lenders care about LTV</h3>
              <p>LTV affects:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Approval chances</strong> – very high LTV can lead to
                  rejection or require a guarantor.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest rate</strong> – lower LTV usually means lower
                  rates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Required insurance</strong> – in many markets, LTV
                  above a threshold triggers mortgage insurance or extra
                  guarantees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Maximum loan amount</strong> – lenders often publish
                  maximum LTV limits by product and property type.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – You know the loan amount</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose you buy a home for 250,000 and need a loan of 200,000.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Property value = 250,000</li>
                <li>Loan amount = 200,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                \[ \text{LTV} = \frac{200{,}000}{250{,}000} \times 100 = 80\%.
                \]
              </p>
              <p>
                Your LTV is 80%. You are at the upper end of the “standard”
                band: many lenders still accept this, but a slightly larger down
                payment could unlock better rates.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – You know the down payment</h3>
              <p>
                You want to buy a property worth 300,000 and can put down 60,000
                (20%).
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Property value = 300,000</li>
                <li>Down payment = 60,000</li>
                <li>Loan amount = 300,000 − 60,000 = 240,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                \[ \text{LTV} = \frac{240{,}000}{300{,}000} \times 100 = 80\%.
                \]
              </p>
              <p>
                Again, your LTV is 80%. Increasing your down payment to 75,000
                (25%) would reduce LTV to 75% and likely improve your borrowing
                conditions.
              </p>

              <h2>How to improve your LTV</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Increase your down payment</strong> – save more or use
                  equity from another property.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose a cheaper property</strong> – a lower price
                  with the same savings reduces LTV.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Renegotiate after value increases</strong> – if the
                  property value rises and you have repaid principal, your LTV
                  falls.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Avoid additional borrowing secured on the same
                    property</strong
                  >
                  – extra loans raise LTV again.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The calculator uses the values you enter and does not replace
                  a professional appraisal.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Lenders may use slightly different valuation criteria or
                  include other secured debts on the same property.
                </li>
                <li>
                  LTV is only one factor; income, credit history, and
                  regulations also matter.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Loan-to-Value (LTV) – FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is a good LTV ratio for a mortgage?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Many lenders consider ≤ 80% LTV as “good”: you bring at
                    least 20% equity. This often gives access to better interest
                    rates and may avoid mortgage insurance or additional
                    guarantees. Very low LTV (for example 50–60%) is even safer
                    and can unlock the best conditions.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is LTV based on purchase price or appraised value?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Lenders typically use the lower of the purchase price and
                    the appraised market value. If you buy below market value,
                    your effective LTV may be lower than you expect; if you
                    overpay relative to the appraisal, your LTV may be higher
                    and the bank may reduce the loan amount.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does LTV affect refinancing as well?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Yes. When you refinance, the bank recalculates LTV using the
                    current loan balance and current property value. If your LTV
                    has fallen thanks to repayments or price increases, you may
                    qualify for better rates or be able to remove mortgage
                    insurance.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is a higher LTV always bad?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Not necessarily. A higher LTV lets you buy with a smaller
                    down payment, which can be useful if you have strong income
                    but limited savings. However, it usually means higher
                    monthly payments, higher interest costs over time, and less
                    protection if property prices fall.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
